{{Infobox IPA | above = Downstep | ipa symbol = ꜜ◌ | ipa symbol2 = ꜝ◌ | ipa number = 517 | decimal1 = 42780 }} '''Downstep''' is a phenomenon in [[tone languages]] in which if two syllables have the same [[tone (linguistics)|tone]] (for example, both with a high tone or both with a low tone), the second syllable is lower in pitch than the first.
Two main kinds of downstep can be distinguished. The first, more usually called '''automatic downstep''', '''[[downdrift]]'''<ref>Yip (2002), p.148.</ref> or '''catathesis''',<ref>Beckman & Pierrehumbert (1986), p.272.</ref> occurs when high and low tones come in the sequence H L (L) H; the second high tone tends to be lower than the first because of the intervening low toned syllable. That phenomenon is common in African languages, such as [[Chewa language|Chichewa]]. <ref>Myers (1996).</ref> It has also been argued that the same phenomenon causes English sentences, such as ''I <u>rea</u>lly be<u>lieve</u> Ebe<u>ne</u>zer was a <u>dea</u>ler in mag<u>ne</u>sium'' or ''I bought <u>blue</u>berries, <u>bay</u>berries, <u>rasp</u>berries, <u>mul</u>berries, and <u>bram</u>bleberries'' (if the sentences are pronounced with a falling intonation), to fall gradually in pitch, with each accented syllable (here underlined) slightly lower than the last.<ref>Pierrehumbert (1980), pp.139ff, 329ff; Beckman & Pierrehumbert (1986), p.273.</ref>
'''Downstep proper''', or '''non-automatic downstep'''<ref>Connell (2001)</ref>, is another phenomenon found especially in West African languages such as [[Igbo language|Igbo]]. If two high tones are in succeeding syllables (thus in the sequence H H), the second is lower than the first.<ref>Welmers (1974), pp.82ff</ref> In such languages, when two high tones come one after the other, they are at the same height or, if there is a downstep, the second one is lower. The second high tone is also lower than the preceding one if there is an intervening low tone in the sequence H L H as described above. The high tones in a simple sentence tend to descend from the beginning to the end of the sentence in a series of steps, a phenomenon that Is known as [[tone terracing]].
The symbol for the second kind of downstep in the [[International Phonetic Alphabet]] is a superscript down arrow, {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ꜜ}}}}. It is common to see instead a superscript exclamation mark {{angle bracket|{{IPA|ꜝ}}}} because of typographic constraints.
It has been shown that in most, if not all, cases of downstep proper, the lowering of the second high tone is from an intervening low-toned syllable that has dropped out. What was H L H has become H H.<ref>Welmers (1974), p.87.</ref> The missing low-toned syllable creates what is known as a '[[Floating tone|floating tone]]'. An example occurs in [[Bambara language|Bambara]], a language spoken in [[Mali]]. Its [[definite article]] is a floating low tone. With a noun in isolation, it docks to the preceding vowel and turns a high tone into a falling tone: {| |{{IPA|/bá/}}||''river'' |- ||{{IPA|/bâ/}}||''the river'' |} However, when it occurs between two high tones, it downsteps the following tone: {| |{{IPA|/bá tɛ́/}}||''it's not a river'' |- ||{{IPA|/bá ꜜ tɛ́/}}||''it's not the river'' |}
