==In other languages==
Processes of H-dropping have occurred in various languages at certain times, and in some cases, they remain as distinguishing features between dialects, as in English. Some [[Dutch dialects]], especially the southern ones, feature H-dropping. The dialects of [[Zeeland]], [[West Flanders]] and [[North Brabant]] have lost /h/ as a phonemic consonant but use [h] to avoid hiatus and to signal emphasis, much as in the H-dropping dialects of English.<ref>{{OED|h}}</ref> H-dropping is also found in some [[North Germanic languages]], for instance [[Elfdalian]] and the dialect of [[Roslagen]], where it is found already in [[Old Norse#Old East Norse|Old East Norse]]. Loss or replacement of /h/ has also occurred in some dialects of [[Serbian language|Serbian]] and other [[South Slavic languages]].

The phoneme /h/ in [[Ancient Greek]], occurring only at the beginnings of words and originally written with the letter H and later as a rough breathing, was lost in the [[Ionic Greek|Ionic]] dialect. It is also not pronounced in [[Modern Greek]].

The phoneme /h/ was lost in [[Late Latin]], the ancestor of the modern [[Romance languages]]. Both [[French language|French]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] acquired new initial {{IPA|/h/}} in medieval times, but they were later lost in both languages in a "second round" of H-dropping. (However, some dialects of Spanish have reacquired {{IPA|/h/}} from Spanish {{IPA|/x/}} and Latin {{IPA|/f/}}.)

It is hypothesized in the [[laryngeal theory]] that the loss of [h] or similar sounds played a role in the early development of the [[Indo-European languages]].

