'''Jru' ''' ({{IPA-xx|ɟruʔ|IPA}}) is a [[Mon–Khmer languages|Mon–Khmer language]] of the [[Bahnaric languages|Bahnaric]] branch spoken in southern Laos.<ref name=Jacq2004>{{cite journal |last1=Jacq |first1=Pascale |year=2004 |title=The Development of a Lao-based orthography for Jrù |journal=Mon-Khmer Studies Journal |volume=34 |issue= |pages=97–112 |publisher= |doi= |url=http://sealang.net/sala/archives/pdf4/jacq2004development.pdf |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>  It is also known as "Loven", "Laven" or "Boloven" from the [[Lao language|Laotian]] exonym ''Laven'' or ''Loven'', which is derived from the [[Khmer language|Khmer]] name for the [[Boloven Plateau]]. The Jru' people engage in coffee and [[cardamom]] cultivation, as well as other agricultural activities.

==Classification==
Jru' is a variety of [[Laven language|Laven]] which belongs to the Western branch of the Bahnaric languages which also includes such languages as [[Brao language|Brao]].

==Geographical distribution==
Jru' is the native language of the Jru' people, a [[Lao Theung|hill tribe]] indigenous to the isolated mountains in [[Champasak Province|Champasak]], [[Sekong Province|Sekong]] and [[Attapeu Province]]s in the central part of extreme southern Laos.<ref name=Jacq2004/> The variety described here is the most-studied variety that is spoken in [[Paksong District]], Champasak in the towns of [[Paksong]], [[Houeikong]], [[Tateng]], and various nearby villages.

==Phonology==
The sounds and syllable structure of Jru' are typical of the West Bahnaric languages in general. Words are mostly monosyllabic although a few words have [[minor syllable|minor pre-syllables]], retaining the classic Mon-Khmer sesquisyllabic structure. The [[register (phonology)|register]] contrast seen in other Mon-Khmer languages has not been found in Jru' and, in contrast to the surrounding [[prestige language]], Lao, Jru' has not developed phonemic [[Tone (linguistics)|tones]].<ref name=Jacq2004/>

===Consonants===
Similar to the other Mon-Khmer languages of the region, Jru' ditinguishes five places of articulation in its consonant inventory and the stops can be either voiced, unvoiced or (unvoiced) aspirated. The consonants are given below in IPA as laid out by Jacq.<ref name=Jacq2004/>

